## Migration to .NET 8

Your code has **three problematic APIs** that throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete in modern .NET:

| API | Issue | Replacement |
|-----|-------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` signaling |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` without cancellation | Cannot be interrupted cooperatively | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token |

**Additional bug in the original:** Multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls signal the event, but `Reset()` clears it — items can be stranded in the queue.

---

### Option 1: Direct migration (preserves threading model)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new ManualResetEventSlim(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wait for either a new event OR cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle });

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all items (fixes the lost-signal race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes RunLoop via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Option 2: Idiomatic .NET 8 (recommended)

Use `Channel<T>` — purpose-built for producer/consumer with built-in cancellation:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();

    public void Start()
    {
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();         // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // timeout fallback
        try
        {
            await (_processingTask ?? Task.CompletedTask);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Timed out — acceptable
        }
        finally
        {
            _cts.Dispose();
        }
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Key pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **`Thread.Abort` throws at runtime** | It compiles, but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — no silent fallback |
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | If `Handle(item)` takes 30s, the loop won't exit until it finishes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle` if needed |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks |
| **Lost signals** | Original code's `Reset()` after `WaitOne()` can lose queued items — always drain the queue in a loop |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` also obsolete** | `SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9; replace now to avoid churn later |

**Recommendation:** Use Option 2. It eliminates manual synchronization, is thread-safe by design, and integrates naturally with `async/await` and graceful shutdown (e.g., `IHostedService.StopAsync`).
